  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/hemolysis-absolute-primary",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Primary absolute hemolysis index validation against FDA pump in-vitro data",
      "description": "This result represents the central validation evidence for COU2. The CFD model was executed across all five operating points (flow rates: 3, 4, 5, 6, 7 L/min; rotational speeds: 2400, 2600, 2800, 3000, 3200 RPM) using the modified power-law hemolysis model (Giersiepen–Wurzinger coefficients, Bludszuweit correction). Predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) values were compared against in-vitro measurements obtained from the FDA generic centrifugal pump experimental campaign conducted at the FDA CDRH laboratory. The experimental protocol used a closed-loop circuit with bovine blood (hematocrit 33 ± 2%), sampled at 15-minute intervals over a 6-hour test duration. Plasma-free hemoglobin was measured via Drabkin's reagent spectrophotometry. CFD post-processing extracted volume-averaged shear stress histories along 50,000 massless Lagrangian particle trajectories seeded uniformly at the pump inlet. The hemolysis accumulation integral was computed along each trajectory and ensemble-averaged to yield predicted NIH. Monte Carlo uncertainty propagation (N=500 runs, Latin hypercube sampling) perturbed inlet velocity profile, fluid viscosity, and hemolysis model coefficients within their respective ±2σ bounds. Predicted NIH mean: 0.0041 g/100 L; experimental NIH mean: 0.0053 g/100 L; relative error: 22.6%. The 95th-percentile Monte Carlo bound (0.0061 g/100 L) encompasses the experimental mean, indicating the model uncertainty envelope is consistent with measurement scatter. All five operating points fell below the absolute clinical threshold of 0.1 g/100 L. Despite this detailed experimental and computational narrative, no structured Activity node is linked from this result; the generation provenance exists only in this prose description.",
